{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a Trie-based optimization problem. To prevent identity theft, no cow's ID can be a prefix of another cow's ID. This is equivalent to ensuring that in a Trie containing all final IDs, every leaf node represents exactly one cow and no internal node represents a cow. The goal is to minimize the total bits added to achieve this property.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_construction_expert",
      "instructions": "Design an efficient algorithm to insert all N bitstrings into a Trie. For each node in the Trie, track whether it marks the end of an original ID and how many original IDs pass through or end at this node. The total number of nodes can be up to 10^6, so use an array-based Trie implementation for performance in Python."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_optimization_expert",
      "instructions": "Given a Trie where some nodes are marked as 'end-of-ID', determine the minimum number of bits to append to each ID such that no 'end-of-ID' node is an ancestor of another 'end-of-ID' node. This can be modeled as a tree traversal problem: for each node that is an end-of-ID, if it has descendants that are also end-of-IDs, we must extend the current ID to a new leaf. Calculate the minimum cost using a bottom-up or top-down approach to ensure each original ID is extended to a unique leaf in the Trie."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent agent should first use the trie_construction_expert to build a Trie from the input bitstrings. Then, use the greedy_optimization_expert to traverse this Trie. The core logic is: if a node is marked as an end-of-ID, it cannot have any descendants that are also end-of-IDs. If it does, the 'end-of-ID' status must be pushed down to a leaf. The total cost is the sum of the depths of the new leaf positions minus the original depths of the IDs. Combine these to output the minimum total bits added."
}

